Hi, my name is Antoine-Augustin Parmentier and I was born in 1737.
I am a military pharmacist but I am not only known for this.
First of all, do you like potatoes?
Fried, baked, mashed, boiled… Do you have a favorite recipe?
You can eat them in so many ways and they are always good, right?
Think that once upon a time it was not like this. In France it was thought that they brought fever, plague and leprosy!
They only fed them to pigs and it was even illegal to grow them!
I thought so too, even though I was a pharmacist.
However, while I was enlisted in the army during the Seven Years' War I was taken prisoner.
It was not a bad time though, in prison they fed me potatoes and at the end of the war I returned to France.
Once I returned to France I realized that it is the duty of a true citizen to direct his science to the happiness of society.
But they only protect them for show, a lot of people have stolen them from me!
Finally I put armed soldiers to protect a potato field so that people would think they were a precious food.
Then I gave potato flowers to the queen.
First of all I organized potato dinners!
So I started working to make the potato an accepted food!
You may wonder why, well if people think they are such a precious food that they need guards, they will want to eat them.
All my efforts were worthwhile, in fact during the French Revolution and later potatoes were used to avoid famine and save many lives.
Think that even though I've been gone for a long time, people still visit my grave today...
And do you know what they leave on it?
In 1789, the Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen was written, which guaranteed fundamental rights to everyone.
Fought between 1756 and 1763, it was a global conflict involving the major European powers and their colonies.
Two coalitions clashed: on one side Great Britain and Prussia, on the other France, Austria, Russia and Spain.
Famous people such as Benjamin Franklin and Antoine Lavoisier were invited to his dinners
In France, the people lived in poverty while the king and his family lived in luxury, the people were tired of being unfairly taxed and not having a say.
In 1792, the monarchy was abolished and the First French Republic was born.
King Louis XVI was arrested and guillotined, although France went through difficult times, the Revolution inspired many other nations to fight for rights and freedom.
On July 14, 1789, the people of Paris stormed the Bastille, a prison that was a symbol of the king's power, starting the Revolution, a time of great change.
The people demanded more rights and freedom, inspired by ideals such as "Liberty, Equality, Fraternity".
La Ciotat is a commune in the Bouches-du-Rhône department in the Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur region in Southern France. It is the southeasternmost commune of the Aix-Marseille-Provence Metropolis.

Boulodrome Jules Le Noir, Cradle of Pétanque, in tribute to Jules Le Noir who invented pétanque on this field in June 1910.
Inaugurated by Mrs. Rosy Sanna, Mayor of La Ciotat, on February 6, 1999.
I wonder where Antura has gone. He told me to come here, but where exactly am I?
Alright, little one, first we throw the small wooden ball, it’s called the jack.
"Look! I threw it closer to the little ball this time. Am I winning?"
Can I throw again? That one was just a warm-up!
Do you think Jules Le Noir was good at playing too?
I used to come here with my grandfather. He taught me how to play on this exact court.
The sound of the boules hitting each other always reminds me of Sunday afternoons.
I’m not very good, but I love the atmosphere here. It feels like home.
Careful, that one's rolling too far—you’ve got to keep it low and smooth.
This place has so much history. Can you believe pétanque started right here?
Every summer we play a little tournament here, just for fun.
A long time ago, right here in La Ciotat, a man named Jules Le Noir changed the way we play boules.
He couldn’t run anymore because of his legs, so he invented a new way. Standing still with your feet in a small circle.
That’s what "pétanque" means in Provençal, "feet together". It all started in 1910, right here on this ground.
Back then, people used to run up to throw the boules, but Jules showed them you didn’t need to move to be precise.
Now look around you, over a hundred years later, people still come here to play just like Jules did.
Now the goal is to throw your metal boule as close as you can to the jack.
You have to stand inside a circle and keep both feet on the ground while you throw, no stepping out!
We take turns, one team throws, then the other, until all the boules are played.
When all the boules are on the ground, we see which one is closest to the jack.
The game usually goes up to 13 points, but we can play to 5 or 7 just for fun today.
Try to aim gently, and if you want, you can even knock the other team's boule out of the way!
Don’t worry if it doesn’t go perfect, pétanque is about practice, patience, and having fun.
Well played! You've really got the talent to become a champion one day. Here, this is for you, and I hope you'll come back to play with us again.
That was a fun game! Just remember, pétanque is all about having a good time. If you liked it, we’d love to see you back here soon.
The team with the boule closest gets a point for each boule that's closer than the opponent's closest one.
